    <h1>Lesson 2 — Fill-in-the-Blank (Dropdowns)</h1>
    <p class="lead">Select the best word from each dropdown. Each dropdown has three options from the lesson word bank.</p>

    <div class="para">
      <strong>Microorganisms</strong><br>
      Very small organisms are called
      <label class="blank"><select id="q1">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Microorganisms">Microorganisms</option>
        <option value="Bacteria">Bacteria</option>
        <option value="Virus">Virus</option>
      </select></label>.
      Some belong to the domain
      <label class="blank"><select id="q2">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Eukarya">Eukarya</option>
        <option value="Bacteria">Bacteria</option>
        <option value="Archaea">Archaea</option>
      </select></label>, which includes plants, animals, fungi, and
      <label class="blank"><select id="q3">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Protists">Protists</option>
        <option value="Eukaryotes">Eukaryotes</option>
        <option value="Bacteria">Bacteria</option>
      </select></label>.
      Organisms without a nucleus are called
      <label class="blank"><select id="q4">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Prokaryotes">Prokaryotes</option>
        <option value="Eukaryotes">Eukaryotes</option>
        <option value="Autotrophs">Autotrophs</option>
      </select></label>, while those with a nucleus are called
      <label class="blank"><select id="q5">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Eukaryotes">Eukaryotes</option>
        <option value="Protists">Protists</option>
        <option value="Bacteria">Bacteria</option>
      </select></label>.

      Two important ways microorganisms get energy are: making their own food, which makes them
      <label class="blank"><select id="q6">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Autotrophs">Autotrophs</option>
        <option value="Heterotrophs">Heterotrophs</option>
        <option value="Decomposers">Decomposers</option>
      </select></label>, or consuming other organisms, which makes them
      <label class="blank"><select id="q7">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Heterotrophs">Heterotrophs</option>
        <option value="Autotrophs">Autotrophs</option>
        <option value="Protists">Protists</option>
      </select></label>. Organisms that break down dead matter are called
      <label class="blank"><select id="q8">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Decomposers">Decomposers</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
        <option value="Ribosomes">Ribosomes</option>
      </select></label>.

      <br><br>
      <label class="blank"> <select id="q9">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Archaea">Archaea</option>
        <option value="Protists">Protists</option>
        <option value="Virus">Virus</option>
      </select></label> are prokaryotes that often live in extreme environments like hot springs or salty water.
      <label class="blank"> <select id="q10">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Bacteria">Bacteria</option>
        <option value="Fungi">Fungi</option>
        <option value="Protists">Protists</option>
      </select></label> are prokaryotes too, but they have different structures and are found almost everywhere.
    </div>

    <div class="para">
      <strong>Viruses</strong><br>
      A
      <label class="blank"><select id="q11">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Virus">Virus</option>
        <option value="Bacteria">Bacteria</option>
        <option value="Protists">Protists</option>
      </select></label> is a tiny, nonliving particle that reproduces only inside a living cell. The organism it invades is called the
      <label class="blank"><select id="q12">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Host">Host</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
        <option value="Cytoplasm">Cytoplasm</option>
      </select></label>. A virus that attacks bacteria is called a
      <label class="blank"><select id="q13">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Bacteriophage">Bacteriophage</option>
        <option value="Ribosomes">Ribosomes</option>
        <option value="Flagella">Flagella</option>
      </select></label>.

      Viruses come in many shapes and are measured in
      <label class="blank"><select id="q14">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Nanometers">Nanometers</option>
        <option value="Cytoplasm">Cytoplasm</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
      </select></label> (nm). Unlike living organisms, they cannot reproduce on their own — instead, they inject
      <label class="blank"><select id="q15">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Genetic material">Genetic material</option>
        <option value="Toxins">Toxins</option>
        <option value="Ribosomes">Ribosomes</option>
      </select></label> into a host cell, which then makes new viruses until the cell bursts.

      Viruses can cause diseases from the common cold to
      <label class="blank"><select id="q16">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Ebola">Ebola</option>
        <option value="Binary fission">Binary fission</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
      </select></label>. A
      <label class="blank"><select id="q17">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Vaccine">Vaccine</option>
        <option value="Antibiotic">Antibiotic</option>
        <option value="Flagella">Flagella</option>
      </select></label> helps protect people by preparing the immune system. When viruses spread rapidly in one area, it is called an
      <label class="blank"><select id="q18">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Epidemic">Epidemic</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
        <option value="Conjugation">Conjugation</option>
      </select></label>.
    </div>

    <div class="para">
      <strong>Bacteria</strong><br>
      <label class="blank"><select id="q19">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Bacteria">Bacteria</option>
        <option value="Protists">Protists</option>
        <option value="Virus">Virus</option>
      </select></label> are single-celled organisms without a nucleus. Their genetic material is found in the
      <label class="blank"><select id="q20">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Cytoplasm">Cytoplasm</option>
        <option value="Ribosomes">Ribosomes</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
      </select></label>, a gel-like substance inside the cell. Small structures called
      <label class="blank"><select id="q21">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Ribosomes">Ribosomes</option>
        <option value="Flagella">Flagella</option>
        <option value="Pili">Pili</option>
      </select></label> make proteins, while
      <label class="blank"><select id="q22">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Flagella">Flagella</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
        <option value="Cytoplasm">Cytoplasm</option>
      </select></label> may help the bacteria move. Some bacteria also have
      <label class="blank"><select id="q23">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Pili">Pili</option>
        <option value="Toxins">Toxins</option>
        <option value="Eukarya">Eukarya</option>
      </select></label>, hairlike structures that help them stick to surfaces.

      Bacteria can reproduce quickly by
      <label class="blank"><select id="q24">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Binary fission">Binary fission</option>
        <option value="Conjugation">Conjugation</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
      </select></label>, in which one cell splits into two identical cells. They can also exchange genetic material through
      <label class="blank"><select id="q25">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Conjugation">Conjugation</option>
        <option value="Binary fission">Binary fission</option>
        <option value="Vaccine">Vaccine</option>
      </select></label>, which increases diversity. In harsh conditions bacteria may form an
      <label class="blank"><select id="q26">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Endospore">Endospore</option>
        <option value="Decomposers">Decomposers</option>
        <option value="Host">Host</option>
      </select></label>.

      While some bacteria cause illness by releasing harmful
      <label class="blank"><select id="q27">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Toxins">Toxins</option>
        <option value="Ribosomes">Ribosomes</option>
        <option value="Nanometers">Nanometers</option>
      </select></label>, many others are helpful. However, some bacteria become
      <label class="blank"><select id="q28">
        <option value="">— choose —</option>
        <option value="Resistant">Resistant</option>
        <option value="Autotrophs">Autotrophs</option>
        <option value="Ebola">Ebola</option>
      </select></label> to antibiotics, which makes infections harder to treat.
